		</table></td><td class="PanelBodyAlternate" valign="Top"><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3" border="0" width="100%">
			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Bard Aggro<a name="57509"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 19 04 12:40 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">All bard damage does a certain percentage of the aggro that another class would get for the same. That being said, procs are included in that, but pure-hate weapons like the ones from Emp SSra or BoC work just fine. </span></blockquote>
<br />
I wholeheartedly disagree with this, with the possible exception of the hate-procs.
<br />

<br />
DAMAGE gets us just as much hate as any other class.  If I am doing damage and someone else is doing damage, and nothing else is going on.  If my total damage and recent damage are higher than his.. even by a tiny bit.. I HAVE AGGRO.  That is why it works to build a little hate by letting the chants all hit first, you won't lose aggro til they catch up on hate.
<br />

<br />
Other things that generate hate we get less.  
<br />

<br />
If a shaman Malos once and I Harmony of Sound 4 times.... The shaman is getting hit... we bot did resist debuffs, I did it far more often, but his generates much more hate
<br />

<br />
If I slow and the shaman or enchanter uses a slow of the same percentage... much more hate for him
<br />

<br />
If I mezz a mob then an enchanter mezzes the same mob, it breaks and goes to the enchanter.. if I then re-mezz it to save his butt and it breaks again... still goes to the enchanter.
<br />

<br />
If Chorus of Marr generated as much hate per point healed on a raid as cleric healing, bards couldn't survive.
<br />

<br />
Snaring a mob generates some aggro.  I can snare it 4 times then have  a druid land 1 snare, and all else being equal the druid is getting chased (slowly).
<br />

<br />
So to your question.. I would say the combination of snares, chants and a little time before your group jumps in is the optimum way to hold aggro for kiting for a group.
<br />

<br />
Tanking is trickier, you still need the lead time to build up hate.. but regaining aggro is the hard part BoC should help with that. Can't speak much to hate-procing weapons and bards myself</span></td>
